---

Objective.
This study aimed to develop, implement, and validate Mitochondrial Map (mtmap.py), a Python tool for automated extraction, normalization, and visualization of mitochondrial genome annotations, ensuring standardized outputs for comparative genomics, phylogenetics, and educational applications.

Methods.
The tool was implemented in Python (‚â•3.8) using Biopython for GenBank parsing, Pandas for data management, and Matplotlib for visualization. Functional modules were created to: (i) extract CDS, rRNA, and tRNA features; (ii) normalize gene nomenclature using controlled canonical forms (e.g., COI/CO1 ‚Üí COX1, COB ‚Üí CYTB, ATPASE6 ‚Üí ATP6); (iii) apply genome linearization anchored to a user-defined gene (COX1, ND1, CYTB, or specific tRNAs); and (iv) export outputs as annotated maps, presence/absence heatmaps, and CSV tables. Validation employed ten vertebrate mitochondrial genomes from GenBank, covering teleosts, elasmobranchs, lampreys, lungfishes, and basal actinopterygians.

Results.
The pipeline successfully processed ten genomes, including Cyprinus carpio, Oncorhynchus mykiss, Mustelus manazo, Amblyraja radiata, Lampetra fluviatilis, Petromyzon marinus, Protopterus dolloi, and Polypterus ornatipinnis. Extraction of CDS, rRNA, and tRNA was consistent, and gene nomenclature was normalized across records. Anchoring at COX1 enabled comparable linearization. Annotated maps showed conserved gene architecture, with coding genes in pastel colors, tRNAs in pale yellow labeled by amino acid codes, and ribosomal RNAs highlighted. Presence/absence matrices confirmed universal conservation of canonical genes (COX1‚Äì3, ND1‚Äì6, ND4L, CYTB, ATP6, ATP8, 12S, 16S), while differences in tRNA annotation reflected biological variation and database artifacts. Outputs included publication-ready PNG (300 dpi), SVG, and PDF figures, as well as CSV tables with annotations and gene presence matrices.

Conclusion.
Mitochondrial Map (mtmap.py) provides an open-source, reproducible, and user-friendly solution for mitochondrial genome analysis and visualization. By standardizing gene nomenclature and producing robust visualizations, the tool enhances reliability and interpretability of mitogenomic datasets. It is suitable for evolutionary biology, molecular systematics, and biomedical research, and represents a valuable educational resource. Future work will extend to larger datasets, phylogenetic inference modules, and interactive web-based visualization.

Keywords: mitochondrial genome; comparative genomics; bioinformatics; phylogenetics; genome visualization

